[Student "W"]
{[showcards W:SK E:S7 S:S8]

You are South. The bidding has been as shown. You led the \SK, North played the \S7 and East the \S8.

What do you play to the second trick?

Play the \S4.

You cannot see the \S5. The most likely reason is that North has it, and his \S7 is an encouraging signal. The only reason he would encourage you is if he held either the \SA or \SJ.

Together, you two continue to play \Ss to drive out East's \SA. When you get the lead with your \CA you will cash your \S winners and North will still have the \DA for some icing on the cake.

There IS another possibility if East is a better than average Declarer. North just might hold \S 9 7, giving East \S A J 8 5. East played the \S8 as a falsecard to tempt you into playing the suit again. This isn't too likely, but if it happens just congratulate East for the fine play.}
[Play "W"]SK

